data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear failure messages: "Expected collection to not be empty"
    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);

    // "Expected count: 3, Actual count: 5"
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);

    // Verify all are active
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));

    // Returns the element — fails descriptively if missing or duplicated
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
    Assert.AreEqual("Admin", admin.Role);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(list)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, list)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` |
| `list.Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle(list)` |

Also available: `Assert.Contains(item, list)`, `Assert.DoesNotContain(item, list)`, and `Assert.IsEmpty(list)`.

The benefit is **diagnostic failure messages** — instead of just "condition is false", you get exactly what was expected vs. actual.
